////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////
// Acid Test: Environment-Bodied Declarations - Atom Identity & Preemie Sweep
//
// A ForSome whose body is a Let-environment is the atomized form of an
// existential-universal statement: the Rule below concludes ∃x.∀z.P(x,z)
// without using either formal quantifier.
//
// This file guards two fixes.
//
// 1. (atom identity) The body signature used to compute the ProperName of a
//    declared symbol must be a pure function of the body's structure.  It
//    formerly rendered symbols declared by declarations nested inside the body
//    (here, the Let z) via their current ProperName, which is unassigned when
//    the user's document is interpreted but already assigned on symbols
//    arriving in an instantiation via matching.  The user's ForSome and the
//    Rule instantiation's ForSome therefore received different atoms, and the
//    marked ForSome below was indeterminate.  Body-internal declared symbols
//    now render by their raw names, the atoms align, and it validates.
//
// 2. (preemie sweep) The preemie check formerly swept Lets nested inside
//    declaration bodies (here, the Let z inside the ForSome itself).  The
//    interior of a declaration is propositionally atomic and never separately
//    validated, so its conclusions have no validation results and the sweep
//    crashed validation with a TypeError (after first falsely marking the
//    document as a preemie).  Such Lets are now skipped, and their scope is
//    covered by the copy of the body inserted after the declaration.  Loading
//    this file at all regression-tests the crash.
//
// Note: the conclusion P(w,z) inside the user's Let-environment below is
// currently marked as a preemie - a known false positive for atomized ∀-facts
// that is the subject of the ongoing preemie redesign - so this file
// deliberately places no expectation marker on it.

➤ "∃∀: a ForSome whose body is a Let-environment"
{
  Declare Trig, P
  Rule: :{ :Trig(y)  { Let z  P(x,z) } for some x }
  Assume Trig(c)
  { Let z  P(w,z) } for some w ✔︎
}
